dialogue: That’s what he used to eat his pudding, remember?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 08 – The Adhesive Duck Deficiency
dialogue: The only thing in here are blue ice packs.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 08 – The Adhesive Duck Deficiency
dialogue: Oh, god, I am so hungry.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 08 – The Adhesive Duck Deficiency
dialogue: Okay.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 08 – The Adhesive Duck Deficiency
dialogue: Will you shut up? We’re all hungry.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 08 – The Adhesive Duck Deficiency
dialogue: What kind of score are we looking at?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 08 – The Adhesive Duck Deficiency
dialogue: All right, everyone grab flashlights.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 08 – The Adhesive Duck Deficiency
dialogue: Quick, get forks.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 08 – The Adhesive Duck Deficiency
dialogue: I feel like we’re forgetting something important.
He struck out.
With Penny and me, it took two years. Now that I think about it, that was three dates.
No, she was pretty clear about wanting to keep her options open.
The cultural paradigm in which people have sex after three dates.
Never mind, what’s your announcement?
Are you really going to be on NPR?
Very cool, congratulations.
You know, when Sheldon gives you homework, you don’t have to do it.
Hey.
You’d have a better shot with the three-breasted Martian hooker from Total Recall.
Excuse me, I’m sitting here.
Again, I’m right here.
I am here, right? You see me.
How ya doin’, buddy?
Come on, it wasn’t that bad.
Okay, so Kripke played a joke on you.
Raj.
I fell on the floor. All right, he got you, you can get him back.
Are you really admitting defeat?
Good.
What if you could make Kripke look even sillier than he made you look?
You’re not helping.
Sheldon, what you need to do is figure out a way to exact vengeance on Kripke, like, uh, like, how the Joker got back at Batman for putting him in the Arkham Asylum for the Criminally Insane.
No, no.
Okay, uh, that’s the spirit, but, um, let’s dial it back to a non-lethal form of vengeance.
Let’s keep thinking.
This is brilliant, Sheldon. How are we going to deploy it in Kripke’s office?
Let me guess, motion sensors?
I gotta say, I am really impressed. This is truly the Sheldon Cooper way to get even. (Sits down. There is a flatulent noise)
Who is that with him?
And the board of directors. Abort! Abort!
At least they don’t know it was you.
I think it upsets Sheldon when you play with the food.
It upsets Sheldon when you play with the Sheldon.
Yeah. Hey.
Sure. The more, the merrier.
Sheldon…
Relax, it’ll be fine, sit down, you guys.
That’s where Sheldon sits.
I am. Are you interested in physics?
Actually, my tests of the Aharonov-Bohm quantum interference effect have reached an interesting point. Right now, we’re testing the phase shift due to an electric potential.
Yes, I am. You want to see a simulation on my laptop?
Hey, look, it’s Howard and his girlfriend Bernadette.
Yeah, no, I got it.
Ah, terrific. We’re getting the electron accelerator set up. We should be ready to go day after tomorrow.
You’re welcome to come.
Excuse me?
Yeah? So?
What are you talking about?
Has it ever worked?
Howard, relax, I’m not interested in your girlfriend.
I believe you.
What did I do now?
What?
You do have a problem with her hanging out with me.
What was I supposed to tell her?
And what would that be?
You told her my experiment was stupid?
Should I, um, leave you two alone?
Okay, good, ’cause I wasn’t really gonna go.
We’re shocked.
Or loud noises, clowns and nuns.
He had a panic attack once when he got his head stuck in a sweater.
I don’t know. Maybe because I’m crazy?
It’s up to you. He didn’t call your experiment stupid.
Tushy face, that is going on Twitter right now.
I’m glad you enjoyed it. Most people aren’t that interested in what I do.
When we watch Frosty the Snowman, he roots for the sun.
We didn’t have a tree when I was growing up.
Mmm, in my family, holidays weren’t so much celebrated as studied for their anthropological and psychological implications on human society.
Mmm, in a way. We presented papers, and then broke off into focus groups and critiqued each other.
Here we go.
Merry Newton-mas, everyone.
No, he doesn’t.
Yeah, you got me. I’m a Leibniz man.
Tomorrow.
Um, tomorrow?
Well, I just, I thought…
You are, it’s just…
I know. And those specials, they change every day.
Okay, sorry.
Um…
Um…
Um…
I drove, Mother. I’m driving now.
Wait, wait, wait. When did you send my mom notes on a paper?
Wait, wait, wait. You had surgery?
No, I heard that.
I just don’t understand why he knows more about your life than I do.
Fine, Mom. How are you?
Now I’m less fine.
No. Sheldon, why didn’t you tell me?
You must be very happy.
Not the time, Sheldon.
I don’t know what you’re talking about.
All right. He “has” a “girlfriend.”
Oh, glad you’re here, uh, sit down, I’ll get you a plate. Mom, you remember Penny.
What?
No!
When did this happen?
Mitzy’s dead?
I don’t believe this. Why am I the last to know?
You’re right. I’m-I’m-I’m-I’m sorry, I’m way out of line!
What is it?
I don’t want tea.
Then why are you telling me?
That’s a lousy conversation starter.
What do you want, Sheldon?
I want that too. Why are you here?
Thank you, that’s very comforting.
It’s not?
You’re right, I do feel better.
You’re my surrogate family?
What the hell is going on?
Are you guys drunk?
How come you didn’t tell me that you and Father were getting a divorce? How come you didn’t tell me you had surgery? How come you didn’t tell me my dog died?
I do.
Once again, I’m driving. I’m right here.
Wait a minute, what are you talking about? What inappropriate behaviour?
What the hell, agreed.
Mother, remember when I was complaining that you don’t communicate with me enough?
I’m over it.
Look at us. Getting ready for a double date with actual women who publicly acknowledge they’re our girlfriends.
Howard, artificial women are your department. You want to take this?
What are you trying to tell me, Howard?
Don’t worry. We’re planning to have sex right on the salad bar.
Got it.
Uh, sorry, Raj. Howard and I are going out to dinner with Penny and Bernadette.
How did we get actual women?
I hope you’re hungry, Bernadette, we’re going to a terrific restaurant.
Great. How come?
Of course, I would never make fun of you.
Oh, gee, why didn’t you say so? They don’t let just anyone have a Web site.
You’re surprised? Your psychic didn’t tell you I was going to be a jerk?
Come on, Penny.
I’m sorry, but facts are facts.
No, if it’s not a fact, it’s not a fact.
You’re welcome. How’s your fish?
Yeah, sure.
Come on, Howard, Bernadette, you’re both scientists. Help me out here.
Maybe we should just stop talking about this.

You know, the best thing about being in a committed, monogamous, mutually supportive relationship is that even if you have different ideas, you can have a spirited debate, yet still care for, even make love with… (she shuts the door in his face) Want your fish? (Opens door, takes fish, closes it again) I knew you were going to do that. Doesn’t make me psychic! Attaboy, Leonard, make it worse. (Opens his own apartment door to find Sheldon, Raj and the two girls playing Rock Band and performing American Woman)
What’s going on?
What the hell is eighth base?
Oh, couldn’t be better.
It’s not just Cylons. Superman’s next.
How can I go out with a woman who believes in psychics?
And that didn’t bother you?
What am I supposed to do, pretend I believe something I don’t whenever I’m with Penny?
Do me a favour, lean over, put your head right here.

What’s your point? In order to keep having a sexual relationship with Penny, I have to give up everything I believe in, my intellectual integrity, the very nature of who I am? I can’t do that, Howard.
What is that?

Hey. Cleaning out the old dryer lint, huh? Not only is it courteous, it’s safety smart. Every year, 15,000 fires are caused by accidental dryer lint ignition. Now you’re supposed to say, wow, what an interesting fact. Come here, you crazy, nerdy guy. I could never be mad at you.
No, I’m sorry. I really am. It’s not right to mock what a person believes in.
Would you be willing to read a book that concisely explains how all psychics are frauds?
Okay, let’s go see your psychic.
Well, yeah, one of us has to keep an open mind.
No, not at all. Let me help you with this stuff.
Great.
I know, and pyramid power and healing crystals.
Really, that’s the line? Psychics are real, but crystals are voodoo?
So what? It’s the same food.
It’s obviously a typo.
You know what? Let’s just get a pizza.
And why is that?
What if they were mobsters who slept with the fishes?
So are our laptops.
We like games.
What about me?
Would I be completely out of line to ask you to shoot him?
How is that going to help them?
What are we supposed to do now?
Does that mean you’ve ruled me out as a suspect?
Hey, there’s no reason for you to be scared.
Hand me the bat.
We’re fine, Sheldon.
Mm-hmm.
Yes, we are. And we’re about to go to bed.
What do you want?
But you don’t like other people.
It’s getting scary here, too.
Did we win? Can we go to bed?
He’s right, Penny. It’s all there.
Great. Good night.
4am.
Just keep walking. (Sheldon checks door then puts TV on his phone)
Who is it?
I’ll send them a basket of muffins.
Where did you get all this stuff?
He just gave it to you?
Sorry, let me help you.
God, Sheldon. What the hell are you doing out there?
It was us. We knocked over a lamp.
We were going to have…
What are you doing? Use the door.
Great, you do that.
I’m lactose intolerant.
Sorry about that.
Looks like Wolowitz got the net electrified.
Don’t you think looking for a new city to live in is a bit of an overreaction?
Oh, no, he’s going to telecommute. Everybody’s really excited about it.
Any place specific or just the Bozeman, Montana Loony Bin?
They call themselves Bozites?
Penny, I told you if you don’t put him in his crate at night he just runs around the apartment.
Mmm, he’s either isolating the terms of his formula and examining them individually, or looking for the alligator that swallowed his hand after Peter Pan cut it off.
Aye, aye, Captain.
Maybe you need a fresh start.
Intellectually about 30 hours. Emotionally about 29 years.
No, I think it’s a firmware problem.
I think Penny likes to skate. The four of us could double.
Yeah, this morning he used a stick of butter as deodorant.
I haven’t seen him this stuck since he tried to figure out the third Matrix movie.
Here, you want my peas?
So roller skating, should we all grab a bite to eat first?
Great. Your mom’s not coming, right?
You had some nice moves out there, Howard.
Yeah. Did you notice all the people looking at us?
Sorry. I’m moving a little slow. I think I bruised my coccyx.
Don’t tell Koothrappali. After you.
Oh, my God! Are you… (falls as well)
Are you okay?
Don’t bark at me. I fell, too.
No, that’s a crazy thing.
That was amazing how you handled him.
It’s not me, it’s my new ringtone. The Joker from Batman.
Me, too, but I paid three bucks for it.
Hello. Yeah, I’m Leonard Hofstadter. Yeah, yeah, he’s my roommate. Oh, God, is he okay? Yeah, alright, alright, I’ll be right there.
Sheldon’s escaped and is terrorizing the village.
Hi. I’m Dr. Hofstadter. Where is he?
Thanks for not calling the cops.
Yeah, well, he’s extra special. Hey, Shelly. What you doing?
Sure, sure. How did you get into this place?
No, I don’t think so. We need to go home now.
If you don’t come out of there, I’m going to have to drag you out.
For God’s sakes. Sheldon, come here!
What?
And you had to barge in here and wake us up in the middle of the night?
Because we didn’t want to be disturbed.
Really? You figured out the graphene problem?
What are you talking about?
Yeah, I’m going to need a little more.
Keep going.
So, you’re going to go work at the patent office?
Sounds like a great plan.
Okay, well, thanks for sharing with us. Good night.
Told you.
Hang on. Black beans, not pinto beans?
Double guacamole?
No cilantro?
Lettuce shredded, not chopped?
You understand why I’m doing this to you?
That’ll be all. That was fun.
I heard about this professor at MIT who melted down, bought a van, and spent the rest of his life as a mobile dog groomer.
Only to shampoo Professor Chambourg’s shih tzu.
Yeah, that’s the only thing wrong with that plan.
Sheldon took our order.
Well, honey, not to complain, but we were starting to think you didn’t either.
Sheldon, come here.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Who’s miserable and alone?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Oh. I used to be like that. Then I got a girlfriend.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Hey, what are you and Bernadette doing for your first Valentine’s Day?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Okay, so to sum up: one giant marble horse, one asinine comment, one lonely man and his chicken. And let’s see, who’s left? Oh, that’s right. My plans. Isn’t anyone going to ask?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: That’s not what I was going to tell you.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Guess who the university is sending to Switzerland to attend a conference and see the CERN supercollider on February 14?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Actually, Professor Norton can’t make it. He threw his back out rock climbing.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: In any case, they’re asking me to fill in for him.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Switzerland. And I get to bring a guest!

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: I am taking Penny.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Sheldon, you got a minute?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Sheldon, I’m not taking you to Switzerland.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Penny.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Yes, but it’ll be Valentine’s Day. We can go sightseeing and skiing and make love in front of a roaring fire in the shadow of the snowcapped Alps.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: I’m sorry, Sheldon.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Yeah, well, I’ve been dreaming about spending Valentine’s Day with a girl since I was six.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Just a minute. This tray contains clues as to what you and I are going to be doing on Valentine’s Day.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: No. But it does involve air travel. Okay, um, let me slice this Swiss cheese with my Swiss army knife, and then you can wash it down with a cup of Swiss Miss instant cocoa.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Uh-huh.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: How does that involve air travel?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: No.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: We’re going to Switzerland to see the CERN supercollider! And ski. We’ll also go skiing.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Well, you’ll ski, I’ll fall, but, yeah, we will be in Switzerland for Valentine’s Day.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Sheldon, we’ve been through this. I’m taking Penny.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Not the roommate agreement.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Oh, for God’s sakes.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Yeah. We also put in what happens if one of us wins a MacArthur Grant, or if one of us gets superpowers, or if one of us is bitten by a zombie.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Sheldon, do you really expect to enforce this?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: No.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Look, Sheldon, I know it’s in the agreement, and if you turn into a zombie, I promise I will not kill you. In fact, I’ll even let you eat my brains. But I am taking Penny to Switzerland.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: It is.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: What do you think? (The sound of Tuvan throat singing comes from Sheldon’s bedroom.)

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Got a bit of traffic this morning, huh? Think it’s gonna rain? Instead of underpants, I covered my crotch with potato salad this morning. Thoughts? Okay, I know what’ll cheer you up, let’s play one of your driving games.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: You really think I belong with Benedict Arnold and Judas?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Come on, Sheldon. Can’t you at least try to understand how much this means to me?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Rupert Murdoch?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: You seen Sheldon?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Yeah. He thinks I betrayed him. I mean, come on, what would you guys do if you were me?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Seriously?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Uh, let’s see. Yup, 30 pieces of silverware.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: What’s going on?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: You made Frodo pancakes?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Why are you doing this?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Thanks. It’s good.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: You hate Babylon 5.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Okay, great. Still not taking you to Switzerland.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Sheldon, I need to talk to you.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Some what?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: You’re not going to Switzerland!

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: She told me that you went behind my back to guilt her into letting you go instead of her.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Well, forget it. I was the one who was invited, I get to decide who goes with me, and it’s Penny, not you!

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: I don’t need to see your presentation. This discussion is over!

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Sheldon, at this point, I would go by myself before I would take you.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Yeah, really.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: I’m sorry you feel that way.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Why don’t you enlighten me?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Just think, this time tomorrow we’ll be in Geneva, Switzerland for our first Valentine’s Day.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Thermal? ‘Cause it’s gonna be cold.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Oh!

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Do you want an allergy pill? ‘Cause I have ’em all. Prescription, nonprescription, foreign, domestic, experimental.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Not really, I’m just an enthusiast.

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Penny? You okay?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: What’s going on?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Well, our plane leaves at 9 a.m. Do you think you’ll feel better by then?

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Hey, Sheldon? Listen, Penny is pretty sick and she’s not going to be able to go to Switzerland. So if you’re still interested, you’re welcome to come. (Sound of Sheldon vomiting in the bathroom)

episode_name: Series 03 Episode 15 – The Large Hadron Collision
dialogue: Yeah, I forgot about all this.
Will you please turn your shirt off?
Hey, Stuart, what’s going on?
Stan Lee does not have a contagious skin disease.

I can’t decide whether I want Stan Lee to autograph my Journey into Mystery 83, first appearance of Thor or my Fantastic Four number five, first appearance of Dr. Doom. (Raj presses his iPod. The theme from Jeopardy plays.) Alex, I’m going to go with what is… you’re a dumbass? (Presses again, his shirt blows a raspberry.)
He does. And in the kitchen. And in the car. And in his pocket.
Hey. Guess who’s going to be at the comic bookstore on Thursday?
Stan Lee.
No, no, Stan Lee.
You have no idea who he is, do you?
Good, good, so, who’s Stan Lee?
Nope.
No.
That’s Bruce Lee.
It’s not that big a deal. You just go down to the court on Thursday and you pay the fine.
Whoa! What do you mean all?
Yeah, okay. No.
That’s what I’m saying.
Oh, come on, why would you do that?
Sheldon’s in jail?
For what?
So tell him to apologize.
Oh, no, that’s terrible. Ooh, the line’s moving. Got to go. Bye.
Look at that. To my friend, Leonard, from Stan Lee, Excelsior!
Oh, hey, buddy. How’d it go?
Yeah, but we all want to hear it from you.
Okay, that’s enough, Howard. The poor guy’s had a tough time. He had to spend the entire afternoon in jail wearing that suit.
Except for Raj.
Why do I always have to carry the heavy stuff?
One more floor, and I’d be the pulled muscle.
Uh, well, we didn’t actually get Chinese food.
Don’t panic, this is better.
We were on our way to the Chinese restaurant when we thought we saw Adam West, so we followed him.
Anyway, we followed the guy to this garage sale, and they had the coolest stuff.
We didn’t even get to go through it all. There could be anything in here.
No. But there is an original final draft Ghostbusters script with actual slime stains! (Raj whispers to Leonard) Oh, you’re right, it’s Ghostbusters 2. Never mind.
Here’s Spock’s head with no body. Here’s Mr. T’s body with no head. Oh, yeah, here’s Spock’s body with Mr. T’s head. I pity the fool who’s illogical.
Okay, bye.
Ooh, look, an Indiana Jones connect-the-dots.
What?
Oh.
And in the darkness bind them.
Seedy underbelly?
He’s not saying it’s a magic ring. You’re not, are you?
No, it is not yours. We all went in on the box together.
How is this maritime salvage?
Guys, it’s stolen. It should go back to Peter Jackson. He made the movies, it belongs to him.
We are not blackmailing Peter J… All right, where’s the ring?
What are you doing?
Give me that.
You always get your way.
Yeah, it’s delicious, the sarcasm’s a little stale, though. Hey, how about this? Until we figure out what to do with the ring, Penny holds on to it.
This ring.
Will you hold on to this for a couple of days?
It’s a prop from a movie, and we’re kind of fighting over it.
How am I looking now?
What was that?
That’s my girl.
No.
We’re not giving him two Jet Skis.
No Jet Skis.
You know what? I am ending this. Penny didn’t want to hold the ring anymore. She gave it to me, I have it. I’m sending it back. Where’s the ring?
Give me that.
Okay, now, this is ridiculous!
I’m not letting go, you let go.
Fine. But can’t we go home and start this?
All right, it starts now.
And it wasn’t when we were driving like this?
You want to talk about endless patience? Penny made me watch all five seasons of Sex and the City.
Oh, crap!
Door. (Leonard tries to unlock the door and drops the keys.)
Last one holding the ring decides its fate. I know, it sounds silly.
Thank you.
I’m out.
It’s in a FedEx box on its way back to where it came from.
Peter Jackson’s office in New Zealand. It wasn’t ours.
I came in here, you guys were all sleeping. The ring was on the floor. No one was touching it.

There wasn’t ever going to be a winner. There was going to be a selfish, petty person with a ring and three people who used to be his friend. Is that really what you guys want? ‘Cause if it is, fine, I don’t want anything to do with you. And I don’t know what happened in that bathroom, but I am not cleaning it up! (Goes to his bedroom. Takes a box from under his bed. Takes out the ring.) My precious.
NEVER!
Hey, Sheldon, I was up in the administration office, and I happened to overhear the name of the winner of this year’s Chancellor’s Award for Science.
Oh, I’m so glad you asked it like that. You.
You won.
Hey, you didn’t want a Slurpee at 7-Eleven, you don’t get glasses.
What?
What, to you, is a large crowd?
Sheldon, you’re being ridiculous.
Sheldon? Sheldon, are you okay?
Sit down, we want to talk to you.
We think we can help you with your stage fright.
We can help you. We can be your team. Like, uh, Professor Xavier and his X-Men.
Yeah, we watched it last week. You said you liked it.
I thought I could try to analyze you and get to the root of your anxiety.
My mother is a highly regarded psychiatrist, and I’ve been in therapy ever since she accused me of breast-feeding co-dependently.
So, Sheldon, how you doing?
I’m sorry, I’ll start again.
Um, I don’t know, maybe.
How did you know you were a giant if everything was to scale?
Why don’t we just talk?
Why don’t I just start? Sometimes people have trouble accepting accolades if, on a subconscious level, they don’t feel they deserve them. Do you think maybe that’s what’s happening here?

But it could be part of your problem. Let me give you an example. When I was eight, I won a ribbon at the science fair for my project, “Do Lima Beans Grow Better to Classical Music.” But my mother pointed out that it was just a rehash of my brother’s earlier “Do Lima Beans Grow Worse to Rock ‘n’ Roll.” I felt so guilty, I gave the ribbon back.
Terrible. I worked really hard on that project. I stayed up all night singing the clown’s aria from Pagliacci to a lima bean sprout.
It wasn’t my fault. I had never seen my brother’s project. And my mother could’ve told me before instead of at the ceremony in front of everyone.
Damn right, I’m angry with my mother. For God’s sake, I was eight years old. She humiliated me. That’s when the bed-wetting started again.
For what?
Wait, that’s it? I thought we had a whole hour!

Good evening, ladies and gentlemen. My name is Dr. Leonard Hofstadter, and it is my very great honour to introduce the winner of this year’s Chancellor’s award for Science and my good friend, Dr. Sheldon Cooper. But before I do, I’d like to share with you a letter from Sheldon’s mother, who couldn’t be here tonight. Isn’t that nice? His mother sent him a letter. She’s proud of him. I wonder what that feels like. Dear Shelly. That’s what she calls him. Shelly, it’s a pet name. You know what my mother’s pet name for me is? Leonard. But I digress. Dear Shelly. I am so proud of… (continues as background noise)
Oh, right. Ladies and gentlemen, our guest of honour, Dr. Sheldon Cooper.
You might want to check YouTube.
It’s already loaded. Just hit play.
Uh-uh, give it a minute.
No, no, I’m good. If my P.E. teachers had told me this is what I was training for, I would have tried a lot harder.
Did you just quote Star Wars?
Oh, my God. I’m lying in bed with a beautiful woman who can quote Yoda. I love you, Penny.
You’re welcome. I just wanted to put that out there.
Good. Glad is good.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Yeah, probably.
Good night.
Seriously? You have nothing better to do than sit around and discuss the possibility of giant ants?
I honestly don’t care.
What do you want from me? I just don’t give a rat’s ass.
Can we please talk about something else? Maybe something vaguely related to life as we know it on this planet?
No, there was no spat.
I don’t want to talk about it.
What? No.
No.
No.
I’m walking away from you now.
Oh, hey.
You don’t have to come if you don’t want to.
Chilli cheese fry?
Really? You love them?
No reason. I’m just glad to hear you’re comfortable saying you love something.
Get into what? Why wouldn’t you love the chilli cheese fries? They’ve been in your life a long time. They make you happy. They deserve to know.
Okay, well, now you’ve had some time to think about it. So, what do you want to say?
How can you not be sure?
No, the place to have the conversation was in bed after I said, I love you, and you said, Thank you, good night.
I am not pushing anything.
What? No, it’s okay. We don’t have to talk ’cause there’s nothing to talk about. Everything’s good.

All right, maybe I overreacted. So we’re in two different places emotionally. So what? And maybe I’m a little ahead of you. That’s fine. You know. In fact, it makes sense, ’cause let’s face it, I’ve been in this relationship two years longer than you.
Really? I wouldn’t know what that’s like.
Yeah, I do.
Yes, that’s what I’m telling you. We are good. We are great.
Wesley Crusher was Wil Wheaton’s character on Star Trek.
This is fun, huh?
It’s good that we got out and did something physical.
Gets us out of our heads. You get in your head, you start to overthink, overanalyze, obsess, you worry. That’s not what we’re doing tonight. Tonight we’re just throwing a ball at some pins.
Mm-hmm, and someday, we don’t know when, maybe you’ll love me back. Ooh, I’m up.
Penny, you’re up.
We really need a strike here.
So just take your time and concentrate.
I’m not pressuring you.
Okay, I’m sorry. I’ll shut up.
Fine. Just tell me what to do, and I’ll do it.
No, let her go.
I’m pretty sure it’s already over.
Hey, where you been?
No, no, it’s fine. I don’t care. I’m over it.
Sheldon, I got you your tangerine chicken. I hope you’re hungry.
Okay.
I don’t know. Why?
Do you want the last dumpling, Sheldon?
So, you guys want to do something tonight?
What about you, Raj?
I never stopped hanging out with you.
You know what? I’ll just spend the evening alone.
Since when do you take after-dinner walks?
Yeah?
Where you going with this, Raj?
So, go.
And you think my presence will help with that?
I’m not going out tonight, Raj.
Very much.
Don’t worry. You’ll meet a girl someday.
Yes, you will, and she’ll be beautiful, and kind and sexy and funny and everything you ever wanted in a woman.
I do, and you’ll fall hopelessly in love and give her your heart. And she’ll take it and grind it into pathetic, little pieces.
I’m pretty sure Martha Stewart never got naked with a room full of big, fat Japanese guys.
Hey, where you been?
For an hour and a half?
How could you get lost? Your phone has GPS.
What the hell was that about?
Oh, we really need to get you a girl.
Oh, just come in!
What do you want, Sheldon?
Tell me why you woke me up or I swear to God I will kill you.
What do you want?
I’m in bed!
Sheldon!
Okay, when you say seeing Penny, what exactly does that mean?
Fine. Why did you have dinner with Penny?
Then why did you have Chinese food with us?
Is it possible he said Bros before Hos?
Sheldon, I don’t care if you want to be friends with Penny.
Yes.
I guess not.
D-don’t be silly. We’re neighbours, we’re going to run into each other, may as well get used to it.
You used to it yet?
Me neither. Oh, Sheldon seemed think that I would be upset about you hanging out with him. But I just want you to know it’s fine.
His mother?
I was going to do that.
No, I don’t want to do it. You can do it.
I just took him for shoes.
Fine. I’ll take him for shoes next Saturday.
You’re taking him to Disneyland?
All right. But let me know if you’re going to stuff him with junk food. I don’t want to bring home a nice dinner for him and see it go to waste.
All I’m saying is give me a heads-up.
And don’t let him go on Space Mountain after he eats. He’ll say he can handle it, but I promise you’ll end up with churro puke on your shoes.
Yeah, don’t let Goofy near him. He’ll have nightmares and I’ll have to deal with it.
Wish I knew. He’s fine with Pluto.
It’s ten o’clock, where have you been?
I was going to see that with him.
And I have food here. You said you were going to call.
We’re not fighting.
Aren’t you going to thank Penny for taking you to Disneyland?
Want a cup of coffee?
Come on. It’s just a cup of coffee.
What am I smelling?
Yeah. Shame he has to wake up.
Smother Sheldon in his sleep? Wouldn’t that be wrong?
Oh. Sure. Absolutely.
Here’s an idea. I’m just throwing it out there, friends who have sex.
Kidding. Just a couple of friends goofin’ around.
Yeah, it’s just one sneeze. (Raj sneezes) You’re on your own.
When you say non-related female, you still mean human, right?
Why didn’t you tell me you knew Elizabeth Plimpton? I am a huge fan of hers!
Okay, fine. Where is she going to sleep?
Thank you. Why is a world-renowned scientist staying in our apartment instead of a hotel?
I can’t believe he’s friends with Elizabeth Plimpton.
She’s here, she’s here. How do I look? Do I look smart?
Oh, I have so many things to tell your biographer.
Hi-lo. Oops. I started to say hi, and then I switched to hello in the middle. It came out hi-lo. Duh. Uh, it’s nice to meet you. I’ve read both your books and most of your papers. I’m Leonard, I live
Are you hungry, thirsty? Can I offer you anything?
Look, it’s you.
Well, who wants to stay in a hotel? With windows that don’t open, those crazy card-shaped keys.
Well, I understand, too.
Oh, (blows a raspberry). I think any university would want you. Except, of course, any university that had already had you. Because they would’ve already wanted you before they, you know, got you.
Uh, sleep night. I mean, obviously, good night. I started to say sleep tight, then I changed my mind in the middle. I swear to God, I’m smart.
Yes?
Is everything all right?
Me neither. Oh, look what I’m reading. It’s you.
I did, but it’s been a while, and I wanted to sound smart over breakfast.
Oh, good. Wasn’t sure it was coming across.
Uh, six.
Sure.
Really? Uh, sure doesn’t read that way.
Wow. You really make science come alive.
Morning, Sheldon.
How do you take your coffee?
Okeydoke.
Something his mother taught him.
Oh, yeah, sure, let me just put this in a travel mug.
Okay, well, I guess I should get dressed so I can take everyone to work. You and Sheldon and Sheldon’s friend, Dr. Plimpton, who you just met. It’ll be fun. Like a clown car.
Hmm? Yeah? What? Huh?
What, uh, you and me? Yeah, we did. Not too long ago. How are you doing with it?
I, um, I don’t follow.
Well, now…
Well…
Come on. It wasn’t my fault.
Penny, I can still drive you.
I didn’t betray Penny.
How am I betraying you?
Yeah, I guess I did.
You still have a cold?
Are you having trouble sleeping? ‘Cause, boy, I was up all night.
No, but I was awake all night.
No, that’s okay. It was something else keeping me up last night. And again this morning. And, I didn’t mind. I was up last night. I was up this morning. I didn’t mind. Those are your clues.
No.
No.
Okay, I’ll give you one more clue. It involved another person.
Hey, you.
Boy, I’m kind of tuckered out. How are you feeling, Elizabeth?
Sure. Black, right?
Coming right up.
Hey, who’s ready for Halo?
I don’t understand.
Elizabeth? What’s going on?
Is she suggesting what I think she’s suggesting?
We’ll all be naked in front of each other.
I thought we had something special.
Hey.
Thanks. It’s really hard to find these in his size. So, listen. I’ve been meaning to talk to you about the other morning.
Yeah, I wanted to explain.
I don’t?
So you’re not judging me?
Nevertheless, I’d like to get one on the record so you can understand why I did what I did.
She let me.
Leonard.
Can I sleep on your couch tonight?
You heard that, huh?
So you agree, he’s nuts.
Believe it or not, he was worse when I met him.
You are so naive. Just like I was seven years ago. (Flasback: The lobby) I’d just started at the university.
Excuse me, I’m looking for Sheldon Cooper’s apartment.
Yeah.
What?
That should have been my first clue.
For all I knew, he was the crazy one. He had this really deranged look.
Sure, it makes sense now. (Flashback. Past Leonard is getting out of the lift). Anyway, I went upstairs and knocked on the door.
Dr. Cooper?
In retrospect, that was clue number two.
I’m Leonard Hofstadter. I called you about the apartment. You said…
What?
Uh, radon?
Telling you? Telling you.
Oh, uh, well, that’s tricky. Um, well, uh, Original Series over Next Generation, but Picard over Kirk.
I don’t understand, their, their existence is conditional?
There’s three?
Okay.
What’s the difference?
Can you do that?
Uh, yeah, experimental physics.
What is that?
Yes.
A car, yeah.
Well, can’t you drive?
Okay, I suppose I could drive you. Well that’s a point in my favour, right?
Come on, I just asked.
Uh, I’m gonna go with preserving the knowledge.
Oh, good. I passed the barriers.
Uh, I guess.
When I have to.
I, I’m sorry, uh, in the morning. Around eight.
Fine. I’ll take it.
Is this it?
So where do you sleep?
If people don’t go in there, and you’re people, and… You are people, aren’t you? Making a joke.
On occasion.
No, I didn’t just move in. First we had to iron out a few details. (Flashback: The apartment)
Does that really need to be in the agreement?
We have a flag?
Okay.
It was the best apartment I’d seen, the rent was very reasonable and after you’ve passed the first three barriers you kind of want to take it all the way.
Okay, how about this? Let me tell you about the first time I brought a girl over. (Flashback to Leonard’s bedroom.)
Shh. Just pretend we’re not here.
I’m sure he’ll go away.
What do you want? I didn’t say come in!
I didn’t even know her 12 hours ago.
But, Joyce, come on.
Do I get some sympathy now?
Actually, I couldn’t get too mad at him about Joyce Kim.
Well, I was doing some government research at the time, you know, military, rocket fuel. It’s kind of secret.
As it turns out, she was a North Korean spy. Luckily, Sheldon drove her out before I revealed anything important. Which I’m not saying I would have.
That was part of it. The other part is what happened with the elevator.
It was, but one night, Sheldon came home from work… (Flashback, the apartment. The settee has now appeared. Leonard, Howard and Raj are playing a video game.)
Hey, Sheldon. This is Howard and Raj. They work at the university, too.
Yeah, not a good idea.
Oh, well, there were some people on the first floor moving out, and they sold it to me for a hundred dollars. Howard and Raj helped me bring it up.
They’re lawn chairs. And there was no place for company.
According to the roommate agreement, I’m entitled to allocate 50% of the cubic footage of the common areas.
I did notify you.
What am I doing in your spam folder?
I’m getting to it. (Back to flashback.)
Ooh, it’s time for Babylon 5!
Why not?
I like it.
There you go– three against one.
But I said no to that.
We can fix that. Let’s leave.
Hey, do you want me to finish working on your man feet or not?
That your dad?
Oh, man. Is that a two-stage rocket?
Oh, this just might be your lucky day.
Well, it turns out I had a little rocket fuel in the apartment.
Mm, Joyce Kim was kind of curious about what I did for a living, and I was going to kind of show it to her. It’s not important. The point is, the guys and I went back to the apartment.
Yeah, we’re really close. Uh, uh, we’re at the apartment. (Flashback.)
The trick is to mix it into Tovex in order to create a combustible gel that will generate over 8,000 kilonewtons of thrust.
Excuse me, but I’ve been working on this a long time. Trust me, it’ll work.
There’s no mistake.
Well, I’ve adjusted the formula.

Okay, I’ve had it with you. You might be an expert on theoretical physics and science-fiction programs and where to sit on a freaking couch, but this is applied physics. And when it comes to applied physic… uh-oh.
A bad thing. A very bad thing. Get the door. Get the door! Get the door! Get the door! Get the door!
Oh. Right.
What’d you do that for? I had plenty of time. (Elevator explodes.)
Not only did Sheldon save my life, he didn’t rat me out to the landlord. Or the police. Or Homeland Security.
So I did something stupid. I’m sure you did stupid things when you were younger. What were you doing seven years ago?
Hey.
Oh, uh, clear nail polish. I had a mani-pedi. Men can get those. Anyway, I may owe you an apology.
I did agree to the thermostat setting, and I shouldn’t have tried to change it.
Okay, I’m sorry.
So, we’re good?
Never mind. Okay if I watch some TV?
Okay, we’ve got power to the laser.
What for? It’s not going to rain.
Howard, do you want to double-check the equatorial mount on the laser? We need it locked onto the Sea of Tranquility.
Relax, it’s just a dirty sock.
Sheldon, the world is filled with dirty discarded socks.
Hey, you know who’d really dig seeing this experiment? Penny.
I don’t know, it’s still a little weird since, you know…
She didn’t dump me. We were just in different places in the relationship.
Screw you guys. I’m gonna go see if she’s home.
We’re up on the roof bouncing laser beams off the moon.
It’s pretty cool. We’ve got a two-meter parabolic reflector and everything. I thought you might want to see it.
Oh, sorry, I didn’t know you were busy. Maybe another time.
Okay, well, yeah, come on up. So, how’d you two guys meet?
Your company?
So, menus.

Let me explain what we’re doing here. Um, in 1969, the astronauts on Apollo 11 positioned reflectors on the surface of the moon, and we’re going to shoot a laser off one of them and let the light bounce back into this photomultiplier.
The laser?
Uh, that’s a great question, Zack.
Don’t worry about the moon. We, we set our laser to stun.
Now, we’ll be able to see the beam when it leaves, but it won’t be strong enough when it comes back to be seen by the naked eye.
Right. Uh yeah, funny. Uh, that device there will measure the photons that return and let us see it on this computer. Raj, get them some glasses.
2.5 seconds for the light to return. That’s the moon! We hit the moon!

Yeah, but, uh, think about what this represents. The fact that we can do this is the only way of definitively proving that there are man-made objects on the moon, put there by a member of a species that only 60 years before had just invented the airplane.
No, thanks.
Have they found a match for you?
Why not?
I’ll help you.
Coming!
Are you drunk?
How did I ruin him?
Come on, he wasn’t that stupid.
Okay, yeah, he’s stupid.
How is that my fault?
Where are we going?
Why? I mean, okay.
How many times have I asked you not to do that?
Where’s Penny?
I wonder why she didn’t say good-bye.
I know. I just thought as an outsider, you might be able to provide a fresh perspective.
Oh, hey.
Okay, I’ll walk down with you. So, last night was fun, huh?
Bummer. Anyway, I was thinking tonight maybe we could catch a movie.
Doesn’t have to be tonight. I’m free pretty much always.
When you say mistake, do you mean a fortunate mistake, like the discovery of penicillin?
No, it’s pretty well imprinted on my brain. Especially the whole rodeo thing.
So, that’s it? Wham, bam, thank you, Leonard?
How am I supposed to let it go? You used me for sex! Morning, Mrs. Gunderson.
Great. Maybe she can have sex with him, and then walk out on him the next morning without so much as a how do you do?
I don’t want to talk about it.
If she can do it, I can do it. If she can do it, I can do it. If she can do it, I can do it. (Knocks on door) I can’t do it.
Oh, hi. Hey. Hi, Leslie.
Uh, I know! It’s been a while!
Right. Right. So how you doing?
Uh, not bad. You remember when we used to have sex and you said that it didn’t mean anything, it was just for fun?
Uh, do you, uh, want to do that again?
She didn’t dump me. We were just in different places in the relationship.
Um, anyway, apparently, it’s okay to go back to people you’re no longer seeing and have recreational sex with them.
So, what do you say?
She’s not coming back.
Thirty feet.
I was a perfectly happy, geeky, little lonely guy, and you ruined me!
Come on. We’re gonna have sex, and it’s not gonna mean a thing!
I’m really starting to think there’s a double standard here.
Alright.
I don’t think that’s going to happen, Sheldon.
So how’s work?
Yeah, we all are.
His girlfriend.
Four months.
Wait a minute– a child? You never see this girl. You just e-mail and text and Twitter. Now you’re considering having a baby?
Still digging the Shamy?
Yeah?
What?
I’d suggest a lubricant, but I have a feeling you fell on some of that as well.
Okay, let’s see.
Well, then let’s un-pause it.
You do what you want, I’m not touching another man’s honey tree.
How about an acetylene torch?
Well, then what do you want us to do?
You have any ideas, Raj?
Okay, come on. Almost there.
Excuse me, could you help us out?
Uh, it’s what controls the arm.
Yeah, yeah, great. Howard, uh, slow down. What do you mean it happened again?

No. You need to give me some advice.
No, specific to my situation.
Empathetic.
I quit.

I know, but I have to go to work, and I made you breakfast.
Uh, before you open that, um, are you familiar with the story of The Shoemaker and the Elves?

No need to. As soon as she flies into California airspace, I’ll feel a disturbance in the Force.
If you could run out and get a PhD, that might make her like you.
Uh, I don’t know. They’re pretty different.
No, we’re kind of taking it slow.
What does that mean?
Yes, Mother.
I change my answer. It, it’s amazing. It’s hot. We can barely keep our hands off each other.
See, this right here, what you’re doing, can you please not do that around Sheldon’s mom?
Of course not. She’s, she’s just a very sweet and God-fearing lady, and you have to be respectful of her beliefs.
Thank you.
East Texas.
Hey, look who’s here.
We just spent two hours in traffic. Did you think to mention to me that you liked our paper?
That’s so sweet, you think I have self-esteem.
Subtle, mom, real subtle.
You mean, my hypothesis. I hypothesized it all by myself.
You still are. Uh, Mom, hey, tell Mary the story about how I made a Van der Graaf generator out of our vacuum cleaner.
So, Mom, you haven’t seen Penny since we got engaged.
We did not. That’s not true. Can I speak to you alone for a second?
It came from Tiffany’s.
Keep walking.

Yes, and we’ll get back to that. But, uh, even with your mother here, you are deliberately hogging all the attention from my mom. You’re like one of those elephant seal pups that steals the milk from two mothers.
Yes, you are a super weaner.
Yeah, you’re right. That is the term I’m looking for. You are a dirty double mother suckler.
Oh, don’t flatter yourself. She likes everybody better than she likes me.
Not once did my mother ever give me any love or affection for just being myself, I always had to earn it.
Thank you.
That’s not what it is.
Oh, me.
I don’t really feel I deserve it.
Okay, Mom, let’s get you back to your hotel before anyone says anything else.
Oh, really? That’s too bad.
Wow. When does that start?
Oh, my mother.
That was really intense.
Hey.
Can it wait until I put a Band-Aid on a goat bite?
I’m gonna guess that your main concern is the time commitment of watching an entire season of a new show.
I get it. Smallville almost wrecked you.
Mmm. My pleasure.
Yeah. I wish I’d fought harder for the rest of ’em.
We’re gonna set a date.
Really good.
And we’ve been busy with our paper.
Yeah, we’ll pick a date when we pick a date.
So, why haven’t we picked a date?
Well, of course I know why. But just for fun, why?
You still want to get married, right?
I don’t know. Because we don’t have a date?
It’s not just the date. We haven’t talked about anything. Big wedding, small wedding, indoor, outdoor?
Is your dad paying for it?
Okay, two friends each.
Fine. I want black-tie.
Okay. Well, then it’s settled. Small indoor church wedding, black-tie, no butterflies.
Great.
Shut up.
Yeah, maybe it’s good you got us talking about this stuff.
Sheldon, I’m not a whiner.
Look, all she’s saying is we are in love so it doesn’t matter if we get married tomorrow or a year from now or 50 years from now.
Yeah, but we’ll be old and gross together.
Are you saying you want to get married?
I’m in. Let’s do it.
Thanks.
Doesn’t sound very romantic.
I’m sure we’ll find a decent chapel.
I know. You think people are gonna be mad?
It is. It is about us.
Right. No surprises.
Uh, well, there, there’s one thing I feel I should tell you.
You know, so we can go into this with no secrets between us.
Remember, uh, a couple years back when I was on that research ship in the North Sea?
Okay, well, there, there was a lot of drinking and craziness going on.
Okay, um, well, there was this girl.
Nothing really. It was just kissing.
And then nothing. I stopped it. But it still bothers me, and I wanted you to know.
Did you ever do anything like this since we’ve been?
Oh, that’s too bad.
Hmm?
Well, like I said, we’re about to get married, and I, I want a clean slate. No secrets.
Would you rather I didn’t tell you?
See, now I’m confused. I mean, what, what am I supposed to do?
I can do that. Uh, uh, from now on, this mouth, you and food, that’s it.
Yeah?
Right.
It wasn’t even very good. She was a smoker, I’d just been seasick.
So, we’re still getting married?
Because we love each other.
And it’s the happiest day of our lives.
Mm, this one comes with music and flowers. Oh, they even stream the whole thing live on the Internet.
‘Cause there’s a lot of gorgeous blondes out there who don’t believe they can land a short, nearsighted scientist. Let’s give them hope.
If you’re not into this, we can do it another time.
Aw. That’s exactly what you said the first time we slept together. (Phone) Oh, excuse me. Sheldon. Hey.
No. Why?
Why not?
What happened now?
Oh, no. Seriously?
Amy broke up with Sheldon.
No.
Buddy, I’m so sorry. Is there anything I can do?
Sheldon, uh, okay, just because you’re going through this with Amy doesn’t mean that all women are bad.
Penny’s on the phone with her.
Hey.
No, I think it’s because we’re eloping.
They’re running a little behind. Should be pretty soon.
Hey, if you’re hungry, there’s a breakfast buffet at the strip club next door.
I don’t think the strippers prepare the meal, but okay. Look, it’s not how I pictured it either, but I’m still glad we’re doing it.
You sure?
And you promise you’re okay with everything from the car?
You’re right. I’m sorry. We have the rest of our lives to dredge stuff up from the past and fight about it. So what do you think? Should we run next door and grab a bite?
Oh, don’t worry. They gave me this vibrating coaster.
Oh, the package that we paid for said the aisle was supposed to be strewn with rose petals.
You know what? It’s fine.
Yup, just want to get married.
This is it.
I love you.
We’re good.
Yes.
Yeah.
It’s okay. I don’t have to say them.

Penny, we are made of particles that have existed since the moment the universe began. I like to think those atoms travelled 14 billion years through time and space to create us, so that we could be together and make each other whole.
I do.
Yeah, I’m so glad you guys could watch.
No, no, no. Hang on. I believe I’m supposed to carry you across the threshold.
Who do you think carries Sheldon to bed when he falls asleep in front of the TV?
I’m okay.
Thank you. Finally, there’s a Mrs. Hofstadter who isn’t disappointed in me.
Everything all right?
Just tell me.
Oh, no. No, come on. I have a friend in you. You said so.
Yeah. Okay, listen. If you’re imagining that it was sexy, it wasn’t. We, we were both drunk, and she smelled like an ashtray. The boat was moving a lot, so I chipped her tooth.
No, she had dental insurance.
Yes. I felt guilty as soon as it happened. I feel guilty every time I see her.
What do I mean? Boy, that’s a toughie.
Well, no, not socially. But, you know, just at work.
I wanted to tell you in the car, but you told me to stop talking
No, of course not. Okay, look, instead of fighting, why don’t we dim the lights, um, get naked and make a baby? I was trying to lighten the mood. It’s not easy. You try it.
I asked you over and over if you were okay. Why would you go through with the wedding if you weren’t?
Okay, listen, I may not have been entirely faithful, but you, you are not easy to lift.
I’m not glowing. I’m upset.
Sure, let’s make it an even hundred.
I wouldn’t.
Well, I may be a man, but I think I’m the one that screwed up on this one.
I figured that out.
Can’t believe I’m spending my wedding night with you.
How am I supposed to sleep? I’ve been married less than 24 hours, and my wife isn’t speaking to me.
Hey.
Of course not.
What are we gonna do?
Please, tell me how I can fix it.
Okay, that is the stupidest thing I’ve ever heard.
You can’t be serious. ‘Cause I messed up and made out with a girl, you’re gonna do the same with a random guy?
What is happening?
Well, trust me, I wish it never happened.
Wait, wait, wait, how is my day-old marriage falling apart becoming about you two?
Oh, we didn’t screw around. We just got drunk and made out.
Call you back. Hey.
I would love that.
If you don’t mind waiting for a Groupon, we can try marriage counselling.
Hey, uh, buddy, can we have some privacy?
Wake up, wake up, wake up.
What? Why?
Uh, first of all, you made that guy cry.
Secondly, I can’t think of a more horrible idea than Penny meeting Mandy.
What, you actually want to meet her?
I’m not being weird. Am I being weird?
Fine, you want to meet her?
How many times do I have to tell you? I have no interest in this woman.
You guys have any idea how much it costs to see a marriage counsellor?
Oh, great, there’s Mandy.
That’s not helpful.
Are we done?
I’m gonna ask her if she’d be willing to talk to Penny, tell her she has nothing to worry about.
What?
Hey.
Uh, do you mind if I sit?
So, um, I’ve been thinking a lot about you and me and the boat.
You know, what we did, when we were drunk.
No, we just made out.
Uh, okay, well, um, I got married recently.
Never gets old. No, no, to a girl. Anyway, I told her what happened between you and me, and she’s concerned about us seeing each other at work.
Because I didn’t want there to be any secrets between us.
What else would it be?
No, I don’t think so. Although, Penny did say exactly that.
You know, on some level, I’ve always believed that I don’t deserve a woman like her.
I mean, she’s really beautiful. She could have any guy she wants. Which is probably why it took her so many years to tell me she loved me.
Too expensive. You’d think I’d be used to women withholding their love. I mean, my mother did. I mean, no matter how hard I tried, she just didn’t have any interest in me.
I wonder if that’s why I have such a dysfunctional relationship with Sheldon. I had a dream the other night that I was in a cave and I was nursing a baby, but the baby had Sheldon’s head on it.
Okay, yeah, um, do you remember when you accused me of trying to sabotage our wedding?
I’ve been thinking about it, and you might be right. But the good news is that I’m pretty sure I know why.
Penny, after all these years, I still feel like maybe I don’t deserve you.
You do?
I don’t even understand why you’re with someone like me. Why would I want to be with someone like me?
Well, how about we stop being so scared of losing each other and just be together?
Good. Because I’ve loved you since the moment we met, and I will keep loving you until the end of time.
Yeah? That’s because you’re beautiful, and your beauty fills my heart with love and song.
Huh? If you think that’s cheesy, buckle up. Penny Hofstadter, will you please stay married to me?
Yes, please.
What is this?
Wow.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: Sure. Hey, want to hear a fun fact about mustard?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: Yeah.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: Hey, you’re early. The movie doesn’t start for an hour.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: What are you talking about?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: When do we leave?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: This was Feynman’s van? That’s so cool.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: So, are you gonna give us a clue where we’re headed?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: India.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: Your house?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: Fun, I’ve never been there.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: If there was a hidden compartment, don’t you think you’d be stuffed in it by now?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: Hey, watch your speed. I hear the Mexican police target tourists.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: Sheldon, can you believe that we’re driving in a van that was owned by one of the greatest scientific minds of the 20th century? It’s like the Batmobile. If Batman was real and a physicist and his car wasn’t cool.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: What?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: And there’s your damsel.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: Yeah, this is nothing more than a physics problem.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: Let’s see, a lever, a lever.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: We’re gonna be here foreever.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: I don’t think the lever’s working.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: There’s gotta be something else we could try.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: Guys, excuse me, not that calling one of the Avengers isn’t a perfectly reasonable choice, but we’re scientists. Don’t you think we can figure this out using actual science?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: They’re basically pure hydrocarbons soaked in fat. Let’s hope the lug nut expands.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: It’s a bachelor party. Lighten up.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: Well, let’s start small. We can always add more.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: We got a flat and couldn’t get the tyre off.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: Thank you.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 03 – The Batchelor Party Corrosion
dialogue: I spent the night in Mexico with Sheldon.
I still don’t understand why you bought that pill caddie. You’re a young man.
It’s just where I need them. You know, she doesn’t have a lot of closet space.
Come on, buddy.
Do I really have to do that now?
It’s harder than I thought.
That helped.
Well, it’s Thai food night.
You’re right. But what? Mexican? Italian? German? Indian? Greek? Cuban? Chinese? Pizza? Barbecue? Korean? Korean barbecue?
Oh, thank God.
You heard him, no.
I guess. I’m just, you know, worried about Sheldon.
I hope so.
No, of course not. I just feel bad.
I did like that he had the weather on it.
I know. And it’s not like we’re abandoning him. Plus, we can FaceTime him whenever we want, you know, once iPhones are invented in his universe.
Hey, we brought you Thai. Where is everything?
I know what you’re doing. You’re trying to get attention so we’ll feel bad for you, but it’s not happening.
Will you knock it off? We’re across the hall.
Buddy, I know me moving in with Penny feels like a big change, but it’s not.
Wuh, what about what you said in the restaurant?
Fine.
Hey, ready for lunch?
That’ll teach her to care about your health.
It wouldn’t be the worst thing if we were more active.
Look at all these activities the university has. Rock climbing club, archery, flag football.
What are you saying? We’re not coordinated enough to play sports?
I got a triple-word score with a double letter Q. If that’s not a time to bust out the scrabble dance, what’s the point of having one? Hey, Barry Kripke started a fencing club.
It’s indoors, so no sunscreen.
No gym shorts that can be yanked down.
Preach.
What about a game of tag on a French schoolyard?
I always wanted to be a swashbuckler when I was a kid.
That’s not why we’re here.
This is easy. I didn’t need to wear a cup.
What?
When was your honour insulted?
Again, that doctor didn’t insult your honour. Just checked your prostate.
Well, good. It’s nice to see your mind off Amy.
Oh. I hate to say it, but it sounds like he’s interested in her.
Oh, buddy, I get that you don’t like it, but it’s not really up to you.
Look, even if it’s not him, Amy’s probably going to date someone at some point.
Of course. She deserves to be happy.
Listen, I should warn you that maybe asking Amy out isn’t a good idea.
And now the crazy version of what I just said.
Wow. That, that was crazier than I thought.
I’m surprised you wanted to go to a sports bar, Sheldon.
If you’re cranky and retaining water, I have a theory.
Maybe you should consider women who aren’t in serious relationships with your closest friends?
Three.
You’re just sweaty from exercise.
I know it only takes one doctor’s finger.
We should let you guys talk.
Look at me go.
What’s going on?
Just tell me.
Oh, well, that kind of stinks.
What are we going to do?
I’d love to, but we need liquid helium and our shipment’s on back order for a month.
That shirt brings out the blue in your eyes.
Let’s go check to see if the university has any helium in reserve.
Hey, Barry, we’re in trouble. We need liquid helium, does the department have any we can use?
Come on, Barry, there’s a Swedish team trying to run our experiment before us. Can’t you spare any?
Yes.
What are you doing?
We’d have to go to every Party City in California.
Who is he?
How does he get the helium?
Oh, hey. I just heard back from the liquid helium guy.
He’s got what we need and can meet us tonight.
The man restocking the cereal shelves.
He handed you the box directly and called you Stretch.
Do you want liquid helium or not?
Then I’m going to tell him we’re in.

We’re just bending the rules a little. We have grant money to do the experiment, so we’re going to spend it on the helium we need. It’s not like when Dr. Goldfarb claimed he bought an electron microscope and he was really just keeping a Russian girl in an apartment in Van Nuys.
Sure. So, are we doing this?
Remember? Don’t ask too many questions?
A little, but if I may quote Einstein, the pursuit of science calls us to ignore the rules set by man.
Done.
Before I answer, may I just say your skin has never looked better.
That must be him.
Hey.
Uh, I’m Leonard. This is my friend…
Uh, yeah, uh, right here.
What ya doing, Skippy?
Look, you can trust us. We’re respected scientists.
My friend does make a decent point about the money. I don’t feel comfortable just handing it over up front.
I don’t think it matters if this is a stalemate or an impasse or a Mexican standoff. What are we gonna do here?
Afraid so, Skippy.
All right, let’s all just calm down. Nobody wants to report anybody.
No, no, no. Wait, don’t go. Just let me explain. We’re physicists, and we’re trying to prove a hypothesis that we’ve been working on for over a year.
Okay, but now there’s this Swedish team that read our paper and they’re trying to beat us to our own discovery. We really need this helium.
Here’s the money. Can we do this?
It’s actually pretty common in our field. There’s not much you can do about it.
Will you stop with that already?
And tipping his hat to the cleaning lady didn’t do that?
Let’s just start the experiment.
We’re not getting caught.
The dealer doesn’t care, Kripke has no authority over us, and you being related to a metal container would explain a lot. Help me hook this up.
What?
What is it?
It’s probably USC or UCLA.
Let’s not jump to conclusions. A lot of things start with U.
Listen, we can do the experiment as planned and beat the Swedish team to the punch, or we can kiss our dreams good-bye because we were to afraid to break a few rules.
Ma’am.
Thank you for coming back.
No, nothing. We just changed our mind.
Thank you.
You know what? It’s fine. Keep the money. We just want to be done with this.
He wants more money.
Is Ernest Goes to Jail the only prison movie you’ve seen?
Thank you, Barry.
Can you give us a minute?
Me neither, but what other choice do we have?
I promise this is the last time.
It says right here on Wikipedia. A Mexican standoff is a confrontation between at least three parties.
Did you hear about this study that found people that were cool and popular at 13 have problems succeeding later in life?
You tell me, you woke up in bed with one.
Why is he writing to you?
I’m the one who thought of Spockumentary.
How long have you known Adam?
And what are you getting him back for?
My brother was mean to me, too.
When did we get a wall safe?
When did we get a floor safe?
There’s a security camera?
You have a will?
Will Wil want it?
You bought her a ring?
Oh, man, I’m sorry, that must have been devastating for you.
You did go pfft.
Just like you.
I know. I also can’t believe he watched what we did on that couch and still sits on it.
Hey, buddy. How you doing?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
No.
Nirsh.
He didn’t meant that.
Well now instead of idolizing fictional characters, you can focus on the real people who are already in your life.
Thank you.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: Well, he’s having a rough time. Amy broke his heart, the DVR cut off the last minute of Doctor Who. That crow followed him home.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: Ah, well, what’s this? A pot of oatmeal? Or, thanks to you, what I will now call gloatmeal.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: You’re in a good mood.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: What brought this on?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: Hey, I made French toast sticks.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: Ah, I also made oatmeal.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: I don’t understand why we’re leaving so early for the movie.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: What? I don’t want to do that.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: This is the movie that big soda doesn’t want you to see.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: So you’re actually okay with invading your friend’s privacy?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: Not really.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: You just happen to have those in the car?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: By stalking them?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: Can I see?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: I know, but you guys make being a crappy friend look fun.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: Yeah, okay, I see him. It looks like they’re having a nice time. I wish I could hear what they’re saying.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: Okay, we saw them. Can we go catch the movie?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: Are we gonna be much longer? I really have to go to the bathroom.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: What happened?

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: Yeah.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: I don’t know if you want to do that, I was just, okay, never mind.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 08 – The Mystery Date Observation
dialogue: You really should.
Well, we’re having everyone over.
Otherwise we’d love to.
Yeah, poor us.
I know. I feel so grown up.
Really? How many grown-ups do you know who have Mr. Spock oven mitts? Hey, the recipes are on my iPad. Will you pull ’em up?
My birthday.
It’s just the four digits, month and day.
Let me see. Yeah, there. What number were you putting in?
You don’t know my birthday, do you?
Well, what is it?
May what?
You don’t know your own husband’s birthday.
Your birthday is December 2, you grew up on Perkins Street, the last four digits of your social are 7 6-2 1, and the odds of me letting you forget this are zero.
Next we need a teaspoon of pepper, which, I believe, was also the name of your childhood dog.
Baby.
Justin.
Nice try. NSYNC forever.
Face it, you can’t stump me. I am the king of husbands. I know that you don’t like the lingerie that I got you on Valentine’s Day. I know you hate the word moist. I know…
Because it’s orange and you think it makes you look like a slutty carrot.
Sure you did.
What? I didn’t know you had a journal.
No, it doesn’t.
Come on, don’t be mad. It was a long time ago, and it was an accident.
I didn’t even know what it was. I saw it on your nightstand. I picked it up.
You know me, I’m a big ol’ bookworm.
Well, hey, okay. Let me make this up to you. Sometimes I keep an online journal. I want you to read something that I wrote.
Okay. Well, then I’ll read it to you. It’s from the day we first met. Beauty, thy name is Penny.
Fine. Mmm, Penny’s beauty, like our love, grows more with each passing day.”
Why would I lie?
Well, you didn’t read it right. The new Star Wars is coming. Gah.
Be right there. Hi, lover.
I’m sorry about the journal. I want to make it up to you. So I’m gonna let you post a shame photo of me on Facebook.
Don’t want people to see what, huh? A little bit of this?
Huh? Some of this? And, since it’s Thanksgiving, an extra helping of this?
I’m glad you had a nice time with Amy.
Since when do you hum songs?
You were just humming.
How does your brain feel about calculating the surface tension of the domain walls?
Well, hum it again. Is that the SpongeBob song?
Whatever. Can we just get back to this?
It’s just an earworm. It’ll come to you.
Is this what we’re doing the rest of the night?
Which is crazy, since rock and roll is all about good customer service.
Eh, that just means going barefoot.
Put on some headphones.
How does he keep coming up with new ways to be annoying?
Come on. I take care of him all day long. You do it for once.
What do you want, a medal? It was your gum.
I love you.
Oh, yeah, he got a tuba.
Hey, can we please get back to work?
All right, just stop. This is ridiculous.
Thank you.
That’s a trick question, right?
Yup, she’s right. For every Newton who had a psychological issue, there’s an Edison who was just a jerk. That could totally be you.
There goes our shot at him living on the roof.
I don’t know. It’s pretty catchy.
Well, now that you can focus again, what do you say we get back to surface tension of domain walls?
Aw. Am I like the dryer sheets of your heart?
Aw.

episode_name: Series 09 Episode 11 – The Opening Night Excitation
dialogue: Guys, tickets already went on sale.
